'''Katherine A. Heinrich''' (born February 21, 1954){{r|otj}} is a mathematician and [[mathematics education|mathematics educator]] who became the first female president of the [[Canadian Mathematical Society]]. Her research interests include [[graph theory]] and the theory of [[combinatorial design]]s. Originally from Australia, she moved to Canada where she worked as a professor at [[Simon Fraser University]] and as an academic administrator at the [[University of Regina]].{{r|pouliot}}
==Education and career== Heinrich was born in [[Murwillumbah]], [[New South Wales]].{{r|otj}} As an undergraduate at the [[University of Newcastle (Australia)|University of Newcastle]] in Australia, Heinrich graduated as a University Medalist in 1976.{{r|un}} She continued at Newcastle as a graduate student, and completed her doctorate there in 1979.{{r|pouliot|mgp}} Her dissertation, ''Some problems on combinatorial arrays'', was supervised by Walter D. Wallis.{{r|mgp}}
Heinrich joined the mathematics faculty at Simon Fraser University in 1981,{{r|pouliot}} and married another graph theorist at Simon Fraser, [[Brian Alspach]].{{r|lh}} She became a full professor in 1987, and chaired the department from 1991 to 1996. While working at Simon Fraser, Heinrich coordinated several outreach activities including a conference for pre-teen girls called "Women Do Math" and later "Discover the Possibilities", a shopping-center exhibit called "Math in the Malls", and a series of national conferences on mathematics education.
From 1996 to 1998, she served as president of the Canadian Mathematical Society, its first female president.{{r|wim}} In 1999, she moved to the University of Regina as academic vice president,{{r|pouliot}} and in 2003 she was confirmed for a second five-year term as vice president. At Regina, she helped establish an institute for French-language education, and built stronger connections between Regina and the [[First Nations University of Canada]].{{r|vp}}
==Research== {{as of|2018}}, [[MathSciNet]] lists 73 publications for Heinrich, dated from 1976 to 2012.{{r|msn}} Several of Heinrich's research publications concern [[Graeco-Latin square|orthogonal Latin square]]s,{{ran|A}} analogous concepts in [[graph theory]],{{ran|D}} and applications of these concepts in [[parallel computing]].{{ran|E}} As well, she has published works on finding spanning subgraphs with constraints on the [[Degree (graph theory)|degree]] of each vertex,{{ran|C}} and on [[Alspach's conjecture]] on [[Edge cycle cover|disjoint cycle cover]]s of [[complete graph]]s,{{ran|D}} among other topics.
