In [[Riemannian geometry]], a field of [[mathematics]], '''Preissman's theorem''' is a statement that restricts the possible [[topology]] of a [[sectional curvature|negatively curved]] [[compact space|compact]] [[Riemannian manifold]] ''M''. Specifically, the theorem states that every non-trivial [[abelian subgroup]] of the [[fundamental group]] of ''M'' must be [[isomorphic]] to the additive group of [[integers]], '''Z'''.<ref>{{citation | last = Ruggiero | first = Rafael Oswaldo | doi = 10.1017/S0143385700000663 | issue = 4 | journal = Ergodic Theory and Dynamical Systems | mr = 1779401 | pages = 1231–1251 | title = Weak stability of the geodesic flow and Preissman's theorem | volume = 20 | year = 2000}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Grant|first=Alexander|url=http://math.uchicago.edu/~may/REU2012/REUPapers/Grant.pdf|title=Preissman's theorem|publisher=University of Chicago Mathematics Department|year=2012}}.</ref>
A corollary of Preissman's theorem is that the ''n''-dimensional [[torus]], where ''n'' is at least two, admits no Riemannian metric of negative sectional curvature.
