{{italic title}}
'''''Why Johnny Can't Add: The Failure of the New Math''''' is a book written by [[Morris Kline]], first published in 1973. In it, Kline severely criticized the teaching practices characteristic of the "[[New Math]]" fashion for school teaching, which were based on [[Nicolas Bourbaki|Bourbaki]]'s approach to mathematical research, and were being pushed into schools in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Jürgen Maass|author2=Wolfgang Schlöglmann|title=New Mathematics Education Research and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Js8NX11zL7QC&pg=PA1|year=2006|publisher=Sense Publishers|isbn=978-90-77874-74-5|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Joseph W. Dauben|author2=Christoph J. Scriba|title=Writing the History of Mathematics: Its Historical Development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oXjMYIonXTYC&pg=PA458|date=23 September 2002|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-7643-6167-9|page=458}}</ref> Reactions were immediate, and the book became a best seller in its genre and translated into many languages.<ref>Fey, James T.. 1978. “U.S.A.”. Educational Studies in Mathematics 9 (3). Springer: 339–353. https://www.jstor.org/stable/3481942.</ref>

